        output='Based on the SpaceX S-1 filing, here is a detailed description of each of the company\'s three operating segments, including their key activities, products, services, revenue sources, and the FY2025 revenue breakdown.\n\n### **1. Space Segment**\n*   **Description & Purpose:** Designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale. It serves as the foundational backbone for SpaceX\'s other segments and external customers.\n*   **Key Products & Services:**\n    *   **Launch Services:** Commercial and government rocket launches using the **Falcon 9** and **Falcon Heavy** vehicles. This includes transporting crew, satellites, and cargo.\n    *   **Launch & Development:** Revenue from long-term development contracts, particularly with government customers (e.g., NASA for crew and cargo missions to the International Space Station).\n    *   **Starship Program:** Development of the next-generation, fully reusable **Starship** transportation system, funded heavily by the segment\'s R&D expenses ($3,004 million in FY2025). Starship is critical for future missions to the Moon, Mars, and beyond.\n*   **Revenue Sources:** Customer launches (commercial and government) and long-term development contracts.\n*   **Revenue Breakdown (FY2025):**\n    *   **Total Segment Revenue:** $4,086 million\n    *   **Breakdown by Type:**\n        *   Launch Services: $2,576 million (63.0% of segment revenue)\n        *   Launch & Development: $1,510 million (37.0% of segment revenue)\n\n### **2. Connectivity Segment**\n*   **Description & Purpose:** Operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband data and communications network powered by the **Starlink** satellite constellation in Low-Earth Orbit.\n*   **Key Products & Services:**\n    *   **Starlink Broadband:** Consumer and enterprise internet service delivered via user terminals.\n    *   **Starlink Mobile:** Satellite-to-mobile texting and voice services for mobile users, reducing "dead zones."\n    *   **Enterprise & Government Solutions:** Connectivity services tailored for specific business and government needs.\n*   **Revenue Sources:** Subscription fees and service sales to consumers, enterprises, and government customers globally.\n*   **Revenue Breakdown (FY2025):**\n    *   **Total Segment Revenue:** $11,387 million\n    *   **Breakdown by Type:**\n        *   Consumer: $7,208 million\n        *   Enterprise & Government: $4,179 million\n\n### **3. AI Segment**\n*   **Description & Purpose:** Operates a vertically integrated AI platform focused on advancing scientific discovery and accelerating SpaceX\'s mission. This segment was formed following the acquisition of **xAI** in early 2026.\n*   **Key Products & Services:**\n    *   **Grok:** A truth-seeking frontier large language model (LLM).\n    *   **AI Solutions:** Consumer and enterprise AI applications and products.\n    *   **X Platform:** The real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform (formerly Twitter).\n    *   **AI Computational Infrastructure:** The compute power and data centers required to train and run AI models.\n*   **Revenue Sources:** Digital advertising (primarily on the X platform), AI solutions & infrastructure services, and consumer subscriptions.\n*   **Revenue Breakdown (FY2025):**\n    *   **Total Segment Revenue:** $3,201 million\n    *   **Breakdown by Type:**\n        *   Advertising: $1,844 million\n        *   AI Solutions & Infrastructure: $1,357 million\n\n### **Summary Table: FY2025 Revenue by Segment**\n| Segment | FY2025 Revenue | Primary Revenue Streams |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Space** | $4,086 million | Launch Services ($2,576M), Launch & Development ($1,510M) |\n| **Connectivity** | $11,387 million | Consumer ($7,208M), Enterprise & Government ($4,179M) |\n| **AI** | $3,201 million | Advertising ($1,844M), AI Solutions & Infrastructure ($1,357M) |\n| **Total** | **$18,674 million** | |\n\n**Key Intersegment Relationship:** The Space segment\'s launch capacity is primarily used internally to deploy and maintain the satellites for the **Connectivity** segment (Starlink), with a significant portion also expected to be allocated to support the **AI** segment\'s infrastructure in the future.',
